The temporal memory [performance test](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/master/tests/integration/nupic/algorithms/temporal_memory_performance_test.py) passes unreliably in CI and locally. Sometimes the test fails to show that the C++ TM is faster than python. See for instance [this build failure](https://ci.appveyor.com/project/numenta-ci/nupic/build/0.1.0.1008). This should be further investigated. However, it is possible that these failures are not symptomatic of worse performance of the C++ implementation and rather the failure is due to random fluctuations of the server load affecting the real time it takes to run each of the TM implementations. If this is the case, one possible solution is to train each model for only one time step in each iteration of the outer loop over time steps, rather than the current test that fully trains each model before proceeding to the next model. This proposal in pseudocode: 
```python
for record in records:
  for model in models:
    times[model] += real time of model.compute(record)
```
This would reduce the tendency for fluctuations in server load to bias the results of the test.

This issue was found while testing #2979

@chetan51 @scottpurdy

Here is a real possibility of something that can result in an incomplete R2-xtra file:

```
void Cells4::saveToFile(std::string filePath) const
{
  OFStream outStream(filePath.c_str(), std::ios_base::out | std::ios_base::binary);
  outStream.precision(std::numeric_limits<double>::digits10 + 1);
  save(outStream);
}
```

When outStream goes out of scope, its destructor calls `close()`, but doesn't check for close error. `close()` doesn't raise. So, if flushing of the buffer failed in the scope of the destructor (e.g., out of disk space), then there would be no exception, and the failure would not be detected, and the file would be incomplete.

`Cells4::saveToFile()` needs to explicitly call `outStream.close()` and check its return value; if the return value indicates that there was an error (get NULL in this case), then an error needs to be propagated out of `Cells4::saveToFile()` that would cause the appropriate exception in the python side of things.

@do3cc did an amazing job this last week to spot why Plone tests fail when [bumping zope.testrunner from 4.4.4 to 4.4.10](https://github.com/plone/buildout.coredev/pull/155): mixing ZopeTestCase based tests and plone.app.testing ones makes both step in each others stacks, thus breaking the setup/teardown contract.

As ZopeTestCase is way more old, it would be handy to have a debug mode that lists all tests that a layer based on ZopeTestCase.

Would a pull request that goes in that direction be accepted?

