At https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/master/graphene/types/argument.py#L28
```py
def __eq__(self, other):
    return isinstance(other, Argument) and (
        self.name == other.name,
        self.type == other.type,
        self.default_value == other.default_value,
        self.description == other.description
    )
```
will always be true in boolean context if `isinstance(other, Argument)`, since the other condition is a tuple of four bools which is truthy no matter the value of the bools. I think what was meant is
```py
def __eq__(self, other):
    return isinstance(other, Argument) and all(
        self.name == other.name,
        self.type == other.type,
        self.default_value == other.default_value,
        self.description == other.description
    )
```
or
```py
def __eq__(self, other):
    return isinstance(other, Argument) and (
        self.name == other.name and
        self.type == other.type and
        self.default_value == other.default_value and
        self.description == other.description
    )
```

Following up on #720 / #752 - would a PR be accepted that made "fields" a default `Meta` option for `Interface`, `ObjectType`, and `InputObjectType`? I believe that would make metaprogramming very straightforward, since fields could be generated as a dict and assigned to Meta. 

Today, this is required (taken from #752 unit test):
```python
class MyInputClass(graphene.InputObjectType):

    @classmethod
    def __init_subclass_with_meta__(
            cls, container=None, _meta=None, fields=None, **options):
        if _meta is None:
            _meta = graphene.types.inputobjecttype.InputObjectTypeOptions(cls)
        _meta.fields = fields
        super(MyInputClass, cls).__init_subclass_with_meta__(
            container=container, _meta=_meta, **options)

class MyInput(MyInputClass):
    class Meta:
        fields = dict(x=graphene.Field(graphene.Int))
```

But I propose to make it possible to do this without a custom subclass:

```python
class MyInput(graphene.InputObjectType):
    class Meta:
        fields = dict(x=graphene.Field(graphene.Int))
```

which would be equivalent to this literal class syntax:
```python
class MyInput(graphene.InputObjectType):
    x = graphene.Field(graphene.Int))
```

